Rob Knight -- Chief Financial Officer

Let me take a shot at that, Brian. The tunnel indirect cost was about $6 million to deal with that, about half OE, half capital. But it had clearly a residual impact on the efficiency of the network. And so breaking out exactly what impact the tunnel had beyond the direct cost is really kind of a difficult task. It definitely contributed to the inefficiencies much broader across the network that led to the $65 million of cost. In terms of what we have to get, without giving a precise number, we clearly have to get -- and can and expect to -- get back on the track. Again, as I said earlier, the recent lingering cost in the third quarter but we're aggressively going to reduce from the $65 million failure cost that we had in the second quarter and that's what it's gonna take to improve the operating ratio year-over-year.

Brian Ossenbeck -- JP Morgan -- Analyst

As a follow-up, Lance mentioned that workers are already a little bit fragile so it gives us time for another PTC update. Just wanted to see how that was trending in the labor side? I guess this is the second call we've heard a call out on vacations to potential headwind on the crew side. So clearly the labor market's tight overall. Just wanted to get your senses to the pipeline being full enough to kind of finally get over the hump here when it comes to getting enough crews in the spots you need it the most?

Cameron Scott -- Chief Operating Officer

On the crew pipeline, as you received the numbers on what we planned to enter in the workforce for August and September, and that pipeline looks very solid for the remainder of the year. So as Lance mentioned, we do not see a crew issue going forward. It will solidify. On the PTC front, our unattended breaking ratio is dropping. That's very positive. And we have initiatives to continue dropping that ratio. Total stops are about the same at this point as we bring more trains on board to that new technology. So net is about the same but good news is we're making very positive progress on the stop ratio.

Operator

Your next question is from the line of Ken Hoexter with Merrill Lynch. Please proceed with your questions.

Ken Hoexter -- Merrill Lynch -- Analyst

Hey, great, good morning. So you mentioned the upside to your outlook on the revenue side but Beth mentioned some tariff impacts on the agriculture. Just wanted to see, Beth, are you starting to see that spread in any sort of way as they've expanded the tariffs and kind of maybe Lance your thoughts on impact on the trade? I know you made some comments at a conference recently; maybe you can expand on that a little bit.

Lance Fritz -- Chairman, President, Chief Executive Officer

Sure, so I'll start, Ken, then let Beth talk specifically about our markets. The concern is that tariffs are just going to basically be a tax, whether it's on US consumption or US products going overseas and generally that's going to reduce the amount of demand. We haven't necessarily seen that wholesale and I'll ask Beth to kind of fill in the blanks in detail. But it's pretty early; those things just went into effect. We have seen some very specific impacts on us but they're pretty granular, right? Inbound on some rail that we buy from Japan. There was a substantial 25% tariff on the last boat that was received and then we've seen some other discreet impacts on customers. But Beth, you want to fill in the blanks?

Beth Whited -- Chief Marketing Officer

So when we talk about agriculture, we aren't really seeing the impacts yet because of the crop uncertainty in South America that I reference. So I think this year the Ag business looks OK in the United States but I think where we're more concerned is in the longer term what the impacts will be. And really, the other impacts on steel, for example, have kind of been in that neutral for us. But anyway, to Lance's point, the longer term free trade impacts are the thing we're really keeping an eye on.

Ken Hoexter -- Merrill Lynch -- Analyst

