Beth Whited -- Chief Marketing Officer

We are currently looking at what we think we might need in 2019. We have some attractive business development opportunities as you suggest but we haven't quite zeroed in on a number yet and we do have some fallout as well so we'll be looking to acquire containers. I don't think we know how many yet.

Ben Hartford -- Robert W. Baird -- Analyst

Is it possible if you have positives -- let's say single-digit type growth -- in domestic intermodal in 2019, are there enough opportunities to improve service and velocity such that net adds could possibly be flat in 2019 to both of those fleets?

Beth Whited -- Chief Marketing Officer

We're just really still in that evaluation process. I'm not sure what to tell you about that at this point. I think it'll get clearer as we get toward the end of the year.

Operator

Next question is from the line of Cherilyn Radbourne with TD Securities.

Cherilyn Radbourne -- TD Securities -- Analyst

Thanks very much and good morning. Wanted to get you to comment on this peak season in a couple of respects. Firstly, one of the things that we're hearing anecdotally is that the peak season may have arrived early and potentially as early as June as BCOs try to get ahead of tariffs. Just wondering if that's a dynamic you've been observing in your business?

Beth Whited -- Chief Marketing Officer

I would not say that we think the peak is arriving early so much as I would say there's a strong demand because of tighter truck capacity. It still feels like they'll be a peak that's kind of in its normal time period.

Lance Fritz -- Chairman, President, Chief Executive Officer

That's really encouraging, Cherilyn, right? From the standpoint of -- it's not like peak's happening now and then it's gonna die off during normal peak. It feels like we've got strong volume entering what feels like it's gonna be a normal peak which is really attractive.

Cherilyn Radbourne -- TD Securities -- Analyst

Okay, and in terms of just your readiness operationally, it sounds like you're feeling good. The other thing I wanted to ask about is, it does sound like it could be a robust peak. Is there any reason to be concerned about the readiness of the Chicago gateway in that context?

Lance Fritz -- Chairman, President, Chief Executive Officer

I don't think so absent let's say product design changes that potentially goof up the network. If the network stays as designed right now among all the participants that interchange at Chicago, Chicago's operating pretty well absent every once in awhile there's a little hiccup here or there. But I think in its current format with the benefits of 12 years that create that have been invested, Chicago should be OK. The one thing to keep your eye on is if anybody starts altering their plans around interchange for intermodal that could have an impact.

Operator

The next question is from the line of Bascome Majors with Susquehanna.

Bascome Majors -- Susquehanna -- Analyst

In response to Allison's questions earlier, you gave some anecdotal examples about share gained from truck into the merchandise business at a micro level. I was curious, do you guys track the opportunity in conversion impact at a macro level? Is this something that you think over the next year or two could really add points to either overall growth or merchandise growth and aggregate?

Beth Whited -- Chief Marketing Officer

We're certainly always watching what is moving out there in the transportation world and what of that we think is convertible to rail either from truck or barge or some other mode of transportation. Clearly, we're using that as a business development tool all the time. What I would say is, I think that those tend to be base hits of some sort. They don't tend to be home runs, those conversions, so we have to pile up a bunch of them to move the needle but that's what we're here to do and the team's actively working on that all the time.

Bascome Majors -- Susquehanna -- Analyst

I appreciate that. You also made some comments about feeling pretty good about the supply demand balance in your pricing power and the domestic intermodal market looking out beyond this year. Do you think your pricing in the domestic business can be better next year than this year at this point just given how the market's progressing and when you were able to price this year's numbers?

Beth Whited -- Chief Marketing Officer

I'm not sure how to answer that. I think if you keep having tight supply, obviously that's gonna allow everybody to be in an environment where you can achieve hopefully two things: volume growth and pricing growth. The way we calculate our numbers, as people have told you, is somewhat backward looking so some of the impacts from the ability to get pricing that we're doing right now you're gonna continue to see as you go out over the next several quarters.

